{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10054,"record_hash":"sha256:d6b8bd9e83160162ee71c51607b0ad1da71a6c3a3dc01dc1bcd880742d1df6a1","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:12.744Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n ## Minimal Tool Draft\n \n The minimal agent-facing surface should be three read tools:\n \n ```text\n-but agentlog sessions [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\n+but agentlog sessions [branch [<branch>] | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\n but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\n but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--from start|end|<index>] [--limit N]\n ```\n@@\n There should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\n agent performs with these tools.\n+\n+If `branch` is provided without a branch name, it should mean the current branch.\n+That keeps the common prompt easy:\n+\n+```text\n+Check whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n+```\n+\n+The CLI can keep storage terms like `session_key` and `turn_key` internally, but\n+human-facing help should prefer `session id` and `turn id`. \"Key\" reads like an\n+implementation detail.\n \n ### `sessions`\n@@\n JSON should include:\n \n - requested target, if any\n - `session_key`\n - `updated_at`\n+- `started_at`, if known\n - `turn_count`\n - `record_count`\n - `related_turn_keys`, only for targeted lookup\n+- match evidence, not confidence:\n+  - `matched_by`, for example `branch_observed`, `review_observed`,\n+    `change_observed`, or `explicit_reference`\n+  - `matched_turn_keys`\n+  - other observed branch/review/change keys, when present\n - source metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n - latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n+- latest user/assistant excerpts, when cheap to derive\n \n This command should not hydrate transcript records. It is an index card.\n+It should be sorted by most recent activity first.\n@@\n JSON should include one entry per capture turn:\n \n+- stable turn index within the session\n - `turn_key`\n - `previous_turn_key`\n - `capture_kind`\n - `captured_at`\n - `record_count`\n+- record index range\n - environment snapshot status\n - observed branch/review/change target keys\n - first and last record timestamps\n-- optional tiny previews of first and latest user text\n+- tiny previews of the first/latest user text and latest assistant final/status\n+  text, when available\n+- compact tool/command counts, when available\n \n This command should not return full transcript records. It should stay cheap\n enough that an agent can run it before deciding what to read.\n+\n+When `--limit` returns only part of the session, the response must say so with\n+coverage metadata such as `showing_turns`, `total_turns`, `has_more_before`, and\n+`has_more_after`. A receiving agent should not mistake the last 20 turns for the\n+whole session.\n@@\n JSON should return:\n \n - `session_key`\n - `turn_key`\n - turn metadata\n - ordered transcript records\n - record index/range metadata\n - `next` and `previous` cursors or offsets when more records are available\n \n The command must be bounded by default. Backfilled turns can contain thousands\n of records, so `records` should never accidentally dump a whole historical\n session because one turn was large. If the agent needs more, it can read the\n next or previous range.\n \n-`--from end` matters. For handoff, the latest records in a huge backfill are\n-usually more useful than the oldest records. The oldest records can still matter\n-for the original task prompt, so `--from start` should remain available.\n+`--from end` should be the default. For handoff, the latest records in a huge\n+backfill are usually more useful than the oldest records. The oldest records can\n+still matter for the original task prompt, so `--from start` should remain\n+available.\n+\n+Even when reading from `end`, return records in natural transcript order within\n+the selected window. For example, \"last 100 records\" should render oldest to\n+newest across those 100 records.\n+\n+Responses should include stable range metadata:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"range\": {\n+    \"start_index\": 4900,\n+    \"end_index\": 4999,\n+    \"total_records\": 5000,\n+    \"has_more_before\": true,\n+    \"has_more_after\": false,\n+    \"previous_from\": 4800,\n+    \"next_from\": null\n+  }\n+}\n+```\n \n The first version should not add record-kind filtering. Return ordered records\n with clear `kind`, `role`, `tool_name`, and redacted text fields. The consuming\n agent can decide to skim tool calls, skip noisy tool results, or read them when\n tests/errors/commands matter.\n+\n+Record-kind, path, command, or error filtering can come later if real catch-up\n+sessions prove that raw bounded windows are still too noisy.\n+\n+## Simulation Findings\n+\n+Six agent-consumer simulations mostly agreed on the shape:\n+\n+- keep the command set small\n+- make the first response a triage surface, not just opaque ids\n+- default to recent/tail-oriented reads for catch-up\n+- keep raw ordered records as truth\n+- expose ambiguity instead of product-y confidence scores\n+\n+The main pressure points were:\n+\n+- `sessions` must explain why each session matched the requested target\n+- `timeline` must include enough previews and metadata to choose turns without\n+  opening every turn\n+- `records` must support reverse-friendly pagination with stable indexes\n+- subagent/compaction/session lineage is useful, but only when the provider data\n+  makes it reliable\n+\n+The simulations also surfaced tempting additions that should stay out of v1:\n+\n+- automatic main-session selection\n+- `--interesting` filters\n+- generated summaries as required output\n+- record-kind/path/error filtering\n+- a separate `search` command\n+- a combined `show` command\n+\n+Those are all plausible later, but they hide too much policy in the first\n+version. The primitive layer should expose enough facts for the receiving agent\n+to choose, not choose for it.\n+\n+### Catch-Up Heuristics For The Consuming Agent\n+\n+The intended agent behavior is:\n+\n+1. Start with `sessions branch`.\n+2. Prefer recent sessions with multiple incremental turns.\n+3. Treat one-turn backfills and sidecar sessions as secondary until previews\n+   show they matter.\n+4. Use `timeline` to find latest user corrections, assistant final/status\n+   messages, tests, errors, and branch/change observations.\n+5. Read `records` from the end of the most relevant turns first.\n+6. Page backward or read the start of a backfill only when the current goal or\n+   original instructions are unclear.\n+\n+The agent should read:\n+\n+- exact user messages for intent and constraints\n+- final/status assistant messages for claimed outcome and remaining work\n+- tool calls/results for commands, tests, failures, and changed files\n+- assistant prose for plans and reasoning breadcrumbs when needed\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:12.744Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}